                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Draft Peace Treaty With Italy</hi>: <gloss target="#t_CFMD461">C.F.M.(D) (46)</gloss> 177<note n="63" xml:id="d184fn63">Not printed.</note>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">I. <hi rend="italic">Franco-Italian Frontier</hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Rectification N°4—Tenda and Briga</hi> (Art. 2 (4))<note n="64" xml:id="d184fn64">Paragraph 4 of Article 2 of <gloss target="#t_CFMD461">C.F.M.(D) (46)</gloss> 177 was blank. The remainder
                        of the article was as it appears in the Draft Peace Treaty with Italy
                        referred to the Paris Peace Conference, <ref target="frus1946v04#pg_2">vol.
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 2</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>After an exchange of views the Council agreed to resume discussion of this
                    question at a later meeting.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">II. <hi rend="italic">Treaty Commission. Allied
                        Inspectorate</hi> (Art. 76 and 62)<note n="65" xml:id="d184fn65">For texts
                        of articles 76 and 62 of <gloss target="#t_CFMD461">C.F.M.(D) (46)</gloss>
                        177, see footnote 59, <ref target="#pg_549">p. 549</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The Council adopted the principle that the supervision over the execution of the
                    Treaty should be exercised by the Ambassadors of the Four Powers at Rome acting
                    in concert, for a period of twelve months after the coming into force of the
                    Treaty.</p>
                <p>The Council instructed the Deputies to formulate this decision.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">III. <hi rend="italic">Withdrawal of Allied Forces From
                        Italy</hi> (Art. 64)<note n="66" xml:id="d184fn66">For text of article 64,
                        see footnote 60, <ref target="#pg_551">p. 551</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The Council adopted the principle of an article which would comprise: <list>
                        <label>(<hi rend="italic">a</hi>)</label>
                        <item>the first part of the U.S. Delegation’s proposal stipulating that <pb facs="0579" n="557" xml:id="pg_557"/> all Allied armed forces would
                            be withdrawn from Italy within a period of ninety days from the coming
                            into force of the Treaty;</item>
                        <label>(<hi rend="italic">b</hi>)</label>
                        <item>in regard to the return to the Italian Government of unused currency
                            and property held by the Allies, provisions similar to those adopted in
                            Article 21 of the draft Treaty with Roumania (<gloss target="#t_CFMD461">C.F.M.(D) (46)</gloss> 182).<note n="67" xml:id="d184fn67">
                                <gloss target="#t_CFMD461">C.F.M.(D) (46)</gloss> 182 is not
                                printed. For article 21 of the Draft Peace Treaty with Rumania as
                                referred to the Paris Peace Conference, see <ref target="frus1946v04#pg_68">vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p.
                                    68</ref>.</note>
                        </item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <p>The Soviet Delegation stated that Soviet troops would be withdrawn from Bulgaria
                    under the same conditions as those agreed for the withdrawal of the British and
                    American troops from Italy.</p>
                <p>The Drafting Committee to draw up the final text of the Article dealing with
                    withdrawal of Allied forces from Italy.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">IV. <hi rend="italic">Next Meeting</hi>
                </p>
                <p>It was agreed to hold a private meeting of the Foreign Ministers at 5 p.m. in the
                    office and under the Chairmanship of M. Bidault.</p>
